<TITLE> Rights abuses in Nepal could stoke more violence:UN </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 KATHMANDU, Dec 12 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Nepal risks returning to violence if those abusing human rights are not brought to justice and criminal activities are not contained, the United Nations human rights agency said on Wednesday. A peace deal between the government and the Maoist rebels signed in November last year ended a decade-long conflict in which more than 13,000 people were killed. But the Nepal unit of the UN Office of the High Commissioner for Human Rights (OHCHR) said human rights had been marginalised by political considerations and Nepal had not consolidated the initial improvements. Human rights groups accuse the army and the Maoists of unlawful killings, arbitrary arrests, rape, kidnapping and torture during the war, and say even now some abuses continue. "Prospects for durable peace can only be enhanced by a concerted effort to restore these rights to the core of the peace process," the U.N. agency said in a report published on Wednesday. It urged Nepal to hold those responsible for human rights violations and abuse accountable, resolve issues of discrimination, equality and participation, and protect people's right to life, liberty and security. "Failure to do so risks engendering further violence and deepening social divisions," the agency said. Various marginalised and ethnic groups as well as armed groups have launched often violent protests this year demanding more government jobs and seats in parliament. The UN said more than 130 civilians had been killed in the violence after the peace deal with the Maoists, mainly in the country's central and eastern plains called the Terai. Seven alleged members of armed groups have also been killed by local people in incidents of "popular justice" in the absence of police action, it said. The UN agency urged the armed groups who claim to be pursuing political objectives to end criminal activities and use peaceful means to achieve their stated objectives. The Maoists, who joined the political mainstream